title: Barn Owl
description: Barn Owls can locate prey by sound alone and can catch mice in complete darkness.
range: Found nearly worldwide but are rare in Maine, keeping to the southern tip of the state in York County

title: Blackburnian Warbler
description: Male Blackburnian Warblers fiercely defend their territory, quickly chasing other male Blackburnain intruders through and around the treetops and performing aerobatic displays, like flying in loops and plummeting downward through the branches.
range: Summers in Northeastern North America and winters in South America; occasionally flies off course and visits Greenland, Iceland, and Scotland

title: Common Raven
description: Common Ravens are acrobatic fliers. They can be seen doing rolls and somersaults in the air. They even fly upside down!
range: Nearly worldwide; found in Maine year-round

title: Pileated Woodpecker
description: Pileated Woodpeckers dig rectangular-shaped holes in trees to find ants. Sometimes, these holes get so large and deep that they can cause small trees to break!
range: Northern Canada and much of the United States; seen in Maine year-round

title: Falco sparverius
description: Kestrels save food for lean times by hiding extra food, small creatures they have killed in clumps of grass, tree roots and limbs, and bushes.
range: Alaska, Northern Canada, into the United States, Central Mexico, and the Caribbean; seen in Maine during the summer months

title: Cooper's Hawk
description: Cooper Hawks are among the bird world's most skillful fliers. Their short, rounded wings allow them to fly through dense treetops at high speeds in pursuit of other birds.
range: Southern Canada to Mexico: year-round residents in the southern half of Maine

title: Ruffed Grouse
description: To attract a mate or defend its territory, a male Ruffed Grouse will raise its ruff, puff out its feathers, and beat its wings to create a rapid-fire drumming sound. Some say it sounds like an engine revving!
range: Forests from the Appalachian Mountains across Canada to Alaska; found in Maine woods year-round

title: Red-Tailed Hawk, juvenile
description: Red-tailed Hawks are is the most common hawks in North America. Look for them slowly circling above open fields, or sitting atop telephone poles, eyes fixed on the ground, searching for voles or rabbits.
range: Central Alaska, Canada, across the United States, into Mexico and Central America; seen in Maine during the summer, occasionally year-round

title: American Crow
description: One of the smartest of all birds, Crows can make and use tools. They shape pieces of wood and stick them it into holes in search of food.
range: Canada and the United States; found in Maine year-round

title: Saw-whet Owl
description: The Northern Saw-whet Owl is active only at night and is hard to spot during the day. These owls typically roost in dense vegetation. To see them, put on your night vision goggles and look just above eye level near the trunks of evergreen trees.
range: Southeast Alaska to Central Mexico, found in Maine year-round

title: Sharp-shinned Hawk
description: With its long legs, short wings, and very long tails, the Sharp-shinned Hawk is perfectly formed for navigating in the deep woods at top speeds in pursuit of birds, mice, and other small rodents.
range: Forested areas in the Americas and some Caribbean islands; found in Maine year-round

title: yellowbellied-sapsucker
description: Yellow-bellied Sapsuckers drill holes in trees to release tree sap. They are perfectly equipped to sip the sap from the holes with a specialized, brush-like tipped tongue. Oozing sap also attracts insects, which the Sapsuckers eat.
range: Canada, and Northeastern United States; winters in Mexico and Central America

title: Spruce Grouse
description: Adult Spruce Grouse mostly eat the needles of fir, spruce, and pine trees. But young chicks need extra protein and feast on mushrooms, snails, and grasshoppers.
range: Evergreen forests in Northern and Western North America; found in Central and Northern Maine woods year-round

title: Wild Turkey
description: When they need to, Turkeys can swim by tucking their wings close to their bodies, spreading their tails, and kicking. Turkeys can see three times better than humans and have excellent hearing.
range: From Southern Canada to Northern Mexico; in Maine year-round

title: American Woodcock
description: American Woodcocks have long bills specially designed for pulling earthworms and other insects from the soil.
range: Found in young forests and shrub-filled fields across Eastern North America

title: Wood Duck
description: Wood Ducks are one of the few ducks with strong claws that can grip bark. These claws help Wood Ducks perch in prances to reach nest cavities high in trees near the water. The female Wood Duck takes flight with a loud squealing call and enters the nest hole from full flight - impressive!
range: Year-round in the Southern United States and during summer throughout the United States and Southern Canada

title: Northern (Yellow Shafted) Flicker
description: The Northern Flicker can climb up tree trunks and hammer on wood like other woodpeckers, but it prefers to find food on the ground. Ants are a favorite, and the Flicker digs in the dirt to find them and then slurps them up, using its long, barbed tongue.
range: The Northern Flicker is the most widespread woodpecker species in North America, found from Alaska to Central America

title: Blue Jay
description: Blue Jays eat insects, seeds, and nuts, and they especially like acorns. For this reason, they can often be found hanging around oak trees. Jays store away hidden supplies of food in multiple locations for the winter. Luckily, Jays have remarkable abilities to recall where they have stored food and rarely forget where secret stashes of nuts are located.
range: Southern Canada to Florida and Texas in the United States; found in Maine year-round

title: Hermit Thrush
description: Hermit Thrushes shake bits of grass or leaves with their feet to find insects for food.
range: Forests across Canada, Southern Alaska, and the Northeastern and Western United States

title: Scarlet Tanager
description: Scarlet Tanagers are talented insect hunters. They perch or hover with fast wingbeats to grab insects from leaves, bark, and flowers. They can also catch bees and other flying insects midair.
range: Found from the East Coast to Midwest United States during the summer and in tropical South American forests during the winter

title: Baltimore Oriole
description: The Baltimore Oriole builds remarkable nests that hang down like socks.The nests are woven of thin, long fibers like grass, bark, wool, and horsehair.
range: Central Alberta and Saskatchewan, Canada to South America; summer residents of Maine

title: Cedar Waxwing
description: Cedar Waxwings love fruit, especially raspberries, crabapples, and mulberries. In the winter, they feast on cedar berries; in the spring, before berries are available, they feed on insects.
range: Throughout Canada, the United States, Mexico, Central America, and the Northwestern reaches of Colombia; often seen in Maine year-round

title: Grey Catbird
description: Catbirds can copy the sounds of other birds, frogs, and animals (or even meow like cats!) and combine these sounds to make their own song.
range: Across Central, Eastern United States, and Southern Canada; wintering in Southern United States, Central America, and the Caribbean

title: Rose-breasted Grosbeak
description: ose-breasted Grosbeaks eat a varied diet. They pluck insects from midair,  raid peas from the garden, and eat berries and seeds.
range: North and South America; seen across Maine in late-spring through early fall

title: American Redstart
description: American Redstarts are always on the move and seem hyperactive as they dash through trees after insects, rapidly spreading and closing their tails to startle and flush out possible prey.
range: Summer residents of northeastern, central United States, and southern Canada; winter migration to Central America, South America, and the Caribbean

title: Red-breasted Nuthatch
description: The Red-breasted Nuthatch collects sticky resin from evergreen trees and plasters it around the entrance of its nest hole to keep out predators.  The nuthatch avoids the sticky resin trap by diving directly through the middle of the nest hole.
range: Forests across Canada, Alaska, and the northeastern and western United States; found in Maine year-round

title: Robin
description: Robins prefer insects, especially earthworms, in the morning and fruit later in the day. Robins often find worms by staring, motionless, at the ground with their head cocked to one side, waiting to strike.
range: Year-round residents in the United States; some birds migrate in the winter to warmer regions of the United States and Mexico

title: Brown Creeper
description: The Brown Creepers look for large trees with deeply creased bark where insects can hide. They poke and peck with their long, curved beaks, hunting bugs, spiders, and spider eggs.
range: Throughout North America, from Alaska and Canada to northern Nicaragua; found in Maine year-round

title: Eastern Bluebird
description: Eastern Bluebirds have good eyesight and can see tiny insect prey from more than 60 feet away. They are patient hunters and will perch in trees or on a fence posts and wait for grasshoppers.
range: Forests across Canada, Alaska, and the northeastern and western United States; found in Maine year-round

title: Black-capped Chickadee
description: The Black-capped Chickadee has an amazing ability to remember thousands of hiding places. It hides seeds and other food to eat later, each in a different location.
range: Found year-round from New England to the West Coast into the southern half of Canada and into Alaska

title: House Wren
description: House Wren nests can become infested with mites and other parasites that can hurt the chicks.  To fight this problem, wrens often add spider egg sacs to their nests. Once the spiders hatch, they devour the mites and other nest parasites.
range: The House Wren has one of the largest ranges of any songbird, from Canada to the tip of South America

title: Red Crossbill
description: Red Crossbills eat seeds found in the cones of pine, hemlock, and Douglas-fir trees. Their special bills allow them to break into the cones and pull the seeds out.
range: Found in mature, coniferous forests, including spruce, fir, hemlock, and pine across Canada and the United States

title: White-winged Crossbill
description: A single White-winged Crossbill can eat up to 3,000 spruce cone seeds each day.
range: Central Alaska to Newfoundland, and southwards to the northern parts of the United States.

title: Tree Swallow
description: Tree Swallows bathe by flying low over the water and skimming against the surface; they rise quickly while shaking off water droplets.
range: From Alaska, Canada and much of the United States into Mexico

title: Pine Grosbeak
description: Pine Grosbeaks, both male and female, have pouches on either side of their tongues to store insects, crushed seeds, and tree buds, which they regurgitate to feed their chicks.
range: Canada and the Northern United States; found year-round in Northern Maine and in Southern  Maine in the winter
